    <title>Combined summary - Outbound connections rotation</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T02:12:01.188410+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-August/006504.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context discusses Ivan Pustogarov's proposal to periodically rotate outbound connections every 2-10 minutes in the Bitcoin network. The goal is to improve a node's knowledge about available peers and make the network stronger against partitioning. However, this behavior raises concerns about compromising privacy as it increases the likelihood of a sybil pretending to be many nodes observing the transmission directly. Broadcasting over tor or i2p is recommended for anyone expecting privacy in their broadcasts.The article also highlights an attack on the Bitcoin network, where an attacker listens to transactions on the network, maps out connections, and links together different Bitcoin addresses to learn the IP of the client. The periodic rotation of outbound connections can help blur a client's 8-peers fingerprint over time, making it more difficult for attackers to link different Bitcoin addresses of the same user.There is some confusion about how attackers create a mapping of the nodes on the network. By default, Bitcoin clients advertise their public IP addresses, and an attacker can use this information to deanonymize clients. The attack takes advantage of each NATed client connecting through 8 entry peers and advertising their public IP address to these peers. In August 2014, Ivan Pustogarov proposed the idea of periodic rotation of outbound connections to mitigate the risks associated with a subset of 8 entry nodes that uniquely identifies a user. However, Gregory Maxwell disagreed with this proposal stating that connection rotation would only improve a node's knowledge about available peers and make the network stronger against partitioning. To maintain privacy, broadcasting over tor or i2p is recommended as the traffic is clear text. Pustogarov suggested that every few minutes an outgoing connection would be attempted, even if already at the outbound limit, and better connections would survive for a longer time. In response to Pustogarov's proposal, Jeff Garzik, a Bitcoin core developer, supported the open discussion. The recipient of Pustogarov's email asked for clarification on how this mapping would be produced, raising concerns about distinguishing advertised peers based on their distance from the advertiser. Ultimately, to maintain privacy, broadcasting over tor or i2p is recommended as the traffic is clear text.</summary>
